    },
    {
        ": he was an admirer ": null
    },
    {
        "Erasmus": "Erasmus"
    },
    {
        ". After 1531, Cranmers contacts with reformers from continental Europe helped to change his outlook. The ": null
    },
    {
        "Exhortation and Litany": "Exhortation And Litany"
    },
    {
        ", the earliest English-language service of the Church of England, was the first overt manifestation of his changing views. It was no mere translation from the Latin: its ": null
    },
    {
        "Protestant": "Protestant"
    },
    {
        " character is made clear by the drastic reduction of the place of ": null
    },
    {
        "saint": "Saint"
    },
    {
        "s, compressing what had been the major part into three petitions. Published in 1544, it borrowed greatly from ": null
    },
    {
        "Martin Luthers": "Martin Luther"
    },
    {
        "Litany and ": null
    },
    {
        "Myles Coverdales New Testament": "Coverdale Bible"
    },
    {
        " and was the only service that might be considered to be Protestant to be finished within the lifetime of King Henry VIII.              Only after the death of Henry VIII and the accession of Edward VI in 1547 could revision proceed faster. In 1548, Cranmer finished his work on the Order of the Communion , which was an English ": null
    },
    {
        "Communion": "Eucharist"
    },
    {
        " rite placed within the Latin Mass after the priests own communion. It included an exhortation, a penitential section that included confession and absolution as spiritual preparation, and the administration of the bread and wine. ": null
    },
    {
        "Communion under both kinds": "Communion Under Both Kinds"
    },
    {
        " for the laity was a return to the ancient practice of the church but a departure from the Catholic Churchs practice since the 13th century of giving the laity the bread only. The order also included what would become known as the Comfortable Words and the ": null
    },
    {
        "Prayer of Humble Access": "Prayer Of Humble Access"
    },
    {
        ". The Communion order was incorporated into the new prayer book of 1549 largely unchanged.     While the English people were becoming accustomed to the new communion service, Cranmer and his colleagues were working on a complete English prayer book. Cranmer is credited the overall job of editorship and the overarching structure of the book ; though, he borrowed and adapted material from other sources. He relied heavily on the Sarum rite and the traditional English service books as well as from the English primers used by the laity. Other Christian liturgical traditions also influenced Cranmer, including ": null
    },
    {
        "Greek Orthodox": "Greek Orthodox"
    },
    {
        " and ": null
    },
    {
        "Mozarabic": "Mozarabic"
    },
    {
        " texts. These latter rites had the advantage of being ": null
    },
    {
        "catholic": "Catholic"
    },
    {
        " but not Roman Catholic. ": null
    },
    {
        "Cardinal Quiñones": "Francisco De Quiñones"
    },
    {
        " revision of the daily office was also a resource. He borrowed much from German sources, particularly from work commissioned by ": null
    },
    {
        "Hermann von Wied": "Hermann Of Wied"
    },
    {
        ", Archbishop of Cologne; and also from ": null
    },
    {
        "Andreas Osiander": "Andreas Osiander"
    },
    {
        " . The Church Order of Brandenberg and Nuremberg was partly the work of the latter. Many phrases are characteristic of the German reformer ": null
    },
    {
        "Martin Bucer": "Martin Bucer"
    },
    {
        ", the Italian ": null
    },
    {
        "Peter Martyr": "Pietro Martire Vermigli"
    },
    {
        " or of his chaplain, ": null
    },
    {
        "Thomas Becon": "Thomas Becon"
    },
    {
        ".     Early in the draft process, bishops and theologians filled out questionnaires on liturgical theology. In September 1548, bishops and senior clergy met at ": null
    },
    {
        "Chertsey Abbey": "Chertsey Abbey"
    },
    {
        " and then later at Windsor and agreed that the service of the church ought to be in the mother tongue.  These meetings were likely the final steps in a longer process of composition and revision. There is no evidence that the book was ever approved by the ": null
    },
    {
        "Convocations of Canterbury and York": "Convocations Of Canterbury And York"
    },
    {
        ". In December 1548, the traditionalist and Protestant bishops debated the prayer books eucharistic theology in the House of Lords. Despite conservative opposition, Parliament passed the ": null
    },
    {
        "Act of Uniformity": "Act Of Uniformity 1549"
    },
    {
        " on 21 January 1549, and the newly authorised Book of Common Prayer was required to be in use by ": null
    },
    {
        "Whitsunday": "Whitsunday"
    },
    {
        ", 9 June.       The BCP replaced the several service books then in use and was less complicated than the older system. The prayer book had provisions for the daily offices, scripture readings for Sundays and holy days, and services for communion, public baptism, confirmation, ": null
    },
    {
        "matrimony": "Matrimony"
    },
    {
        ", ": null
    },
    {
        "visitation of the sick": "Anointing Of The Sick"
    },
    {
        ", burial, ": null
    },
    {
        "purification of women": "Churching Of Women"
    },
    {
        " and ": null
    },
    {
        "Ash Wednesday": "Ash Wednesday"
    },
    {
        ". An ": null
    },
    {
        "ordinal": "Wikt:Ordinalnoun"
    },
    {
        " for ordination services was added in 1550. There was also a calendar and ": null
    },
    {
        "lectionary": "Lectionary"
    },
    {
        ", which meant a Bible and a ": null
    },
    {
